G.L. c. 185C, \u00a7 3.proposition: This Court has jurisdiction over this matter under the provisions of G.L. c. 185C, § 3, as the claims involve violations of Massachusetts landlord-tenant law and arise out of the rental property located within Suffolk County.

G.L. c. 223, \u00a7 1.proposition: Venue is proper in Boston Housing Court pursuant to G.L. c. 223, § 1, as the events giving rise to this action occurred in Dorchester, Suffolk County, Massachusetts.

G.L. c. 111, \u00a7 127A.proposition: Under Massachusetts law, Defendant, as a residential landlord, has a duty to provide and maintain the premises in a habitable condition, including compliance with the state’s sanitary code at G.L. c. 111, § 127A and 105 CMR § 410.000.

105 CMR \u00a7 410.000.proposition: Under Massachusetts law, Defendant, as a residential landlord, has a duty to provide and maintain the premises in a habitable condition, including compliance with the state’s sanitary code at G.L. c. 111, § 127A and 105 CMR § 410.000.

105 CMR \u00a7 410.201.proposition: Massachusetts law requires that heat in a habitable dwelling must be maintained at no less than 68 degrees Fahrenheit from 7:00 a.m. to 11:00 p.m., under 105 CMR § 410.201.

M.G.L. c. 186, \u00a7 14.proposition: Under M.G.L. c. 186, § 14, every residential lease agreement in Massachusetts contains an implied covenant of quiet enjoyment, which protects tenants from substantial interference with the use and enjoyment of their leased premises.
